These headlines highlight major events that have occurred in recent weeks. The war in Ukraine continues to escalate, with Russian forces making significant gains. In the United States, the Supreme Court has overturned the landmark Roe v. Wade ruling, which had guaranteed the right to abortion for nearly 50 years. In the United Kingdom, Prime Minister Boris Johnson has survived a vote of no confidence, but his leadership remains in jeopardy. In Texas, a mass shooting at an elementary school has left 19 children and two teachers dead. And in a positive development, global climate talks have ended with an agreement to phase out coal-fired power plants.

name: Darwin Nunez
summary: Darwin Nunez, Liverpool's forward, has received a five-match ban from Uruguay after an incident during Copa America. There have been rumors of Liverpool selling Nunez due to his "unforgivable error," as stated by Arne Slot. However, Liverpool's stance remains clear, with Nunez unlikely to leave. Arsenal's supposed interest in Nunez has been described as a "shock" and a "bombshell" move, with Liverpool setting an asking price. Slot's warning echoes an earlier one from Liverpool regarding Nunez's potential. In a recent incident, Nunez had an exchange with Liverpool's Fabio Carvalho, further fueling speculation about his future at the club.

name: Champions League draw
summary: The Champions League draw has been announced, setting the stage for the upcoming 2024/25 season. The format of Europe's most prestigious club competition has been revised, and the league phase draw pots have been confirmed. The BBC will broadcast the draw, which will take place at 11 am GMT on Monday, August 14th. UEFA has assured that there is no risk of cyber attacks manipulating the draw, which will be assisted by artificial intelligence. The new format introduces a Swiss-style league phase, with 36 teams divided into four groups of nine. The top eight teams in each group will advance to the knockout phase, while the ninth-placed teams will enter the Europa League.

summary: SM Entertainment, the label behind the popular K-pop boy band NCT, has announced that member Taeil has left the group following allegations of sexual misconduct. The news comes as a shock to fans, as Taeil has been a member of NCT since its debut in 2016.
